  abstract = {{$<$}p{$><$}strong{$>$}Abstract.{$<$}/strong{$>$} Accurate assessment of anthropogenic carbon dioxide (CO\textsubscript{2}) emissions and their redistribution among the atmosphere, ocean, and terrestrial biosphere \textendash{} the ``global carbon budget'' \textendash{} is important to better understand the global carbon cycle, support the development of climate policies, and project future climate change. Here we describe data sets and methodology to quantify the five major components of the global carbon budget and their uncertainties. Fossil CO\textsubscript{2} emissions (\emph{E}\textsubscript{FF}) are based on energy statistics and cement production data, while emissions from land use change (\emph{E}\textsubscript{LUC}), mainly deforestation, are based on land use and land use change data and bookkeeping models. Atmospheric CO\textsubscript{2} concentration is measured directly and its growth rate (\emph{G}\textsubscript{ATM}) is computed from the annual changes in concentration. The ocean CO\textsubscript{2} sink (\emph{S}\textsubscript{OCEAN}) and terrestrial CO\textsubscript{2} sink (\emph{S}\textsubscript{LAND}) are estimated with global process models constrained by observations. The resulting carbon budget imbalance (\emph{B}\textsubscript{IM}), the difference between the estimated total emissions and the estimated changes in the atmosphere, ocean, and terrestrial biosphere, is a measure of imperfect data and understanding of the contemporary carbon cycle. All uncertainties are reported as {$\pm$}1\emph{{$\sigma$}}. For the last decade available (2009\textendash 2018), \emph{E}\textsubscript{FF} was 9.5{$\pm$}0.5\&thinsp;GtC\&thinsp;yr\textsuperscript{-1}, \emph{E}\textsubscript{LUC} 1.5{$\pm$}0.7\&thinsp;GtC\&thinsp;yr\textsuperscript{-1}, \emph{G}\textsubscript{ATM} 4.9{$\pm$}0.02\&thinsp;GtC\&thinsp;yr\textsuperscript{-1} (2.3{$\pm$}0.01\&thinsp;ppm\&thinsp;yr\textsuperscript{-1}), \emph{S}\textsubscript{OCEAN} 2.5{$\pm$}0.6\&thinsp;GtC\