ity in CO\textsubscript{2} fluxes. A detailed comparison among individual estimates and the introduction of a broad range of observations shows (1) no consensus in the mean and trend in land use change emissions over the last decade, (2) a persistent low agreement between the different methods on the magnitude of the land CO\textsubscript{2} flux in the northern extra-tropics, and (3) an apparent underestimation of the CO\textsubscript{2} variability by ocean models outside the tropics. This living data update documents changes in the methods and data sets used in this new global carbon budget and the progress in understanding of the global carbon cycle compared with previous publications of this data set (Le Qu\'er\'e et al., 2018a, b, 2016, 2015a, b, 2014, 2013). The data generated by this work are available at {$<$}a href="https://doi.org/10.18160/gcp-2019"{$>$}https://doi.org/10.18160/gcp-2019{$<$}/a{$>$} (Friedlingstein et al., 2019).{$<$}/p{$>$}},
  file = {/home/kristine/Zotero/storage/G42I7MVP/Friedlingstein et al. - 2019 - Global Carbon Budget 2019.pdf;/home/kristine/Zotero/storage/P3WE3L3G/2019.html},
